<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10327&amp;p=115773#p115773</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10327&amp;p=115773#p115773"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Using a bad AT27C080 for UNROM repro]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10327&amp;p=115773#p115773"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">FARID wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />An execute BP on C0BF stops the game constantly<br />By changing BF C0 to BF 00 still it works fine<br /></div><br />That probably means that this location contains code that runs frequently, but not as an IRQ handler.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />An execute BP on C088 DOES NOT stop the game!<br /></div><br />Then that location probably contains data, or code that did not run during the parts of the game that you played.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />It seems that whenever IRQ is not needed, it is the same as Reset Vector, at least in these two games.<br /></div><br />If the IRQ vector is the same as the Reset vector, you can be 100% sure that there's no IRQ handler. The only thing that might cause you trouble in this case is if the game uses the bytes at $FFFE and $FFFF as data (which you can check with a read breakpoint), but I find that very unlikely.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />As a result I feel that I can use Duck Tales 2 or Megaman for the last bank of AT27C080 without worrying about its IRQ<br /></div><br />Yeah, I guess you're right.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Sun Jul 28, 2013 12:03 am</p><hr />
